
'''= (open source) tool to produce map image "tiles" and other photo formats for maps'''

URL = http://mapknitter.org/

=Description=

Sean Gallagher:

"Geographic information systems (GIS) vendors offer their customers tools to produce map image "tiles" and other photo formats for maps. But those tools are specialized and very expensive. Public Lab offers its own Web-based tool for handling this step, called Map Knitter. The Web app, built in Ruby on Rails, allows you to upload images and then rotate, size, and distort them to match an underlying image layer for the location you're trying to map. You can select photo map tiles from Google Maps, Bing Maps, or OpenStreetMap as the background layer or point at custom map tile sources provided as a Tile Layer Support (TLS) service URL.

Once you've pieced everything together, MapKnitter can export the map in five different geographic information system formats—the KML format used by Google Earth, Google Maps Viewer format, OpenLayers, GeoTIFF, and Tile Map Service format—or as a JPG for printing. You can also share the map through the MapKnitter site. So if it's marked as public domain and it's better resolution than existing imagery, Google may suck it into Google Maps to replace what it has."
(http://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2013/12/the-kite-man-cometh-ars-does-diy-open-source-aerial-surveillance/2/)

